# Logic after onboarding in v4.1

This document describes how the new onboarding will affect the rest of the app.


### I expect that V.4.1 (still) *includes* the following steps in the onboarding:
The below affects the rest of the app and its logic:

- **Choice of background** (affects the feed and categories)
- **Notification setup** (affects notification opt-in and the number of notifications sent)
- **Name** (not critical, but used in a few places to personalize the experience)


### The new onboarding *excludes* the following, which will affect the first visit:

- **Mood** (may affect the data feed on the first visit)
- **Goal** (affects the data feed on the first visit)
- **Improve** (affects the data feed on the first visit)


## Other logics we keep unless other is described:

- **Notifications:** The easiest approach is to keep notifications as they are today. Onboarding should not affect them.
- **Favorites:** 25 favorites are added to notifications and the data feed. That can still work from a technical point of view
- **Reopen the app**: today the datafeed differs from first visit to reopen. This could still work form a technical point of view. We keep the logic when user reopen the app.


----

Below, different versions are described â€” with **Version 1** being the most stripped-down version, up to **Version 3**, which is still simplified but includes more options.

## Version 1 ("**first visit**-stripped")

### Change in logic from v4.0 to v4.1

- **Data feed on first visit:** Shows affirmations based on the userâ€™s selections in onboarding. 
- **Favorites**: if user marks an ai generated affirmation as a favorite it will be added to favorite list and will treated as a 'normal favourite affirimtion'
  **Note:** We still show 100 affirmations, which means the AI should generate 100 affirmations (it could be fewer, but I think 30 is far too low).

### What stays the same as in v4.0

- **Reopening the app:** When the user reopens the app, the data feed follows the existing logic in v4.0.
- **Everything except the feed stays the same:** We keep all other pages as they are.
- **Favorites:** Exactly the same. If a user favorites an AI-generated affirmation, it will be saved under Favorites and used in the existing Favorites logic.
- **Notifications:** Stay the same. They are not affected by the AI affirmations â€” except if an AI affirmation is in Favorites.

### Strengths in running Version 1

- The only change happens on the **first visit**, which means that if we see an increase in reopen rate / Day 2 retention, itâ€™s very likely due to better affirmations and better onboarding in the first visit.

### Weaknesses

- If notifications are important for retention and they currently deliver â€œbad affirmationsâ€ that make users stop coming back, this may still be a problem.
- If users feel the app is extremely good during onboarding, but the rest of the app feels less flexible or relevant, it may hurt retention from the first visit to the second visit.
- If we have a problem with users not getting started properly (e.g., because we donâ€™t have a â€œgetting startedâ€ wizard like the one I am have), we wonâ€™t increase retention.


---

## Version 2 ("**Better Notifications**")

Version 2 includes everything from Version 1, with a few additions.

### Change in logic from v4.0 to v4.1

- **Data feed on first visit:** Same as Version 1.
- **Favorites:** Same as Version 1.
- **Notifications logic is updated:** AI-generated affirmations are added to the notification list:
  1. Find up to **25 random favorited affirmations** and add them to the notification list.
  2. Randomly select affirmations from the **AI-generated list** and add them to the notification list.
  3. If we need more affirmations: Randomly select affirmations with the **fewest views** from:
     - the **AI-generated list**, and
     - the **General list**, and
     - the three categories: **"Practice Self-love"**, **"Practice Gratitude"**, **"Enjoy the Now"**  
     Then add them to the notification list.

### Strengths in running Version 2

- On the first visit, most users seem to interact mainly with the affirmation on the datafeed (liking them, viewing them, etc.). So if we create a great first experience with great affirmations, strong notifications can support the user in coming back.

### Weaknesses in running Version 2

- If the first experience is still too thin, notifications may not have much impact.



------


## Version 3 ("**First-visit update + Categories**")

Version 3 includes everything from Versions 1 and maybe 2 if we like, with additional changes.

### Change in logic from v4.0 to v4.1 (Feed, Favorites, Notifications)

- **Data feed on first visit:** Same as Version 1.
- **Favorites:** Same as Version 1.
- **Notifications logic:** Same as Version 2 if we like.

### Change in logic from v4.0 to v4.1 (Categories)

- The **Category icon** on datafeed is changed to **"+"**.
- The **Category page** is renamed from **Categories** to **"Affirmation lists"**.
- The **Category page** is updated with:
  - A new top row called **"My personal affirmations"** (or **"Trineâ€™s affirmations"** â€” whatever we decide).
  - A category icon named **"My affirmations"**:
    - Includes a **settings** icon that takes the user through onboarding again.
    - Shows a **pen** icon that makes it possible to change the name.
    - If the user taps the icon itself, they see the already AI-generated list which is also shown in datafeed.
  - In the same row, a large **"+"** button that takes the user to a new onboarding flow with copy like:  
    **"Create a new set of affirmations**
  - The **Favorites** category is moved down and gets its own line and headline: **"Your favorite affirmations"**.
  - Above **Trending now**, add a headline: **"Inspiration for you"**.
  - all other headlines are deleted - now categories are just placed in a long row.

